  <p class="article-lede">When the Strait of Hormuz closes, the price of tomatoes in Makola Market rises. The connection is not metaphorical. It is a four-channel transmission mechanism that moves at different speeds through Ghana's economy, and it has already started.</p>

  <p>The Strait of Hormuz has been effectively closed to commercial traffic since early March 2026. Approximately 17.8 million barrels per day of oil, roughly 20% of global seaborne trade, have been disrupted. Brent crude surged to $126 per barrel at peak before settling at $112.57 on March 28. This is the largest oil supply disruption since the 1970s energy crisis.</p>

  <p>Ghana is not an oil-dependent economy in the way that Nigeria or Angola are. But Ghana imports approximately 70% of its refined petroleum products. When the global price of crude doubles from budget assumptions, the transmission to every fuel-dependent sector is fast and measurable.</p>

  <p>This article traces that transmission with real data from the National Petroleum Authority's March 2026 pricing windows.</p>

