  <h2 id="four-channels">The Four Transmission Channels</h2>

  <p>The Hormuz shock reaches Ghana through four distinct channels, each operating at a different speed. Understanding these channels is essential for any business operator, investor, or policymaker trying to assess the real impact.</p>

  <h2 id="pump-prices">Channel 1: Pump Prices (2 to 4 Weeks)</h2>

  <p>Ghana's fuel pricing is deregulated. The National Petroleum Authority sets floor prices in bi-monthly windows, and Oil Marketing Companies (GOIL, TotalEnergies, Shell) adjust retail prices based on international benchmarks.</p>

  <p>The transmission is already visible in the data. The NPA's first March pricing window (March 1 to 15) set petrol at GHS 10.46 per liter and diesel at GHS 11.42. The second window (March 16 to 31) jumped to GHS 11.57 for petrol and GHS 14.35 for diesel.</p>

  <div class="risk-box">
    <h4>Diesel: The Critical Number</h4>
    <p>The diesel increase of 25.7% in a single pricing window is disproportionately larger than petrol's 10.6%. This is because Middle East supply disruption affects diesel-grade crude benchmarks more severely. Diesel powers generators, trucks, and farm equipment; it is the fuel of Ghana's productive economy, not just its commuters.</p>
  </div>

  <p>If Brent remains above $110 through April, the next NPA pricing window (April 1) will likely push diesel above GHS 16 per liter. That would represent a total increase of more than 40% from February levels.</p>

  <h2 id="transport-costs">Channel 2: Transport Costs (3 to 6 Weeks)</h2>

  <p>Trotro operators, intercity bus services, and freight carriers pass fuel costs through to passengers and cargo within one to two pricing cycles. The lag exists because of contractual obligations, competitive pressure, and the time needed to renegotiate rates.</p>

  <p>Fresh produce from Tamale to Accra (approximately 600 kilometers) already carries significant transport cost loading. A 30% fuel increase translates to a 10 to 15 percent increase in transported food costs, hitting consumers directly at the market.</p>

  <p>For businesses that move goods, the math is straightforward. A typical freight truck consuming 25 liters of diesel per 100 kilometers now pays GHS 359 per 100 kilometers in fuel alone, up from GHS 286. On an Accra to Kumasi run (250 kilometers), that is an additional GHS 183 per trip. For a fleet making multiple daily runs, the monthly cost increase is substantial.</p>

  <h2 id="generator-fuel">Channel 3: Generator Fuel (Immediate)</h2>

  <p>This channel transmits instantly because there are no contracts to renegotiate. When diesel rises, every business running a backup generator pays more the same day they refuel.</p>

  <p>Ghana's power infrastructure has improved significantly since the severe dumsor period of 2012 to 2016. Grid transmission availability exceeded 98% in 2024, according to GRIDCo data. But distribution-level interruptions remain common, with ECG reporting a System Average Interruption Duration Index (SAIDI) of 32.5 hours in 2024 and system losses of 27%. Most commercial operators maintain backup generators as a structural cost, not an emergency measure.</p>

