  <p>For cold chain operators, the generator cost increase is existential. A cold store running 24 hours faces an additional GHS 432 to 576 per day in fuel costs. Over a month, that is GHS 13,000 to 17,000 in additional operating expense, often the difference between profitability and loss.</p>

  <p>This is why solar-hybrid power systems have become not an upgrade but a survival requirement. At GHS 14.35 diesel, a solar-battery system that reduces generator runtime by 60% saves GHS 259 to 346 per day, dramatically shortening payback from 18 to 24 months to 12 to 16 months.</p>

  <h2 id="imported-goods">Channel 4: Imported Goods Repricing (4 to 8 Weeks)</h2>

  <p>Goods shipped to Ghana from Asia, Europe, and the Middle East face higher freight costs as shipping routes divert around the Cape of Good Hope, adding 10 to 14 days of sailing time and significant fuel costs to each voyage.</p>

  <p>This channel affects pharmaceuticals, electronics, construction materials (steel, cement additives), packaged foods, and industrial inputs. The lag is longer because supply contracts and inventory buffers absorb the initial shock. But by May 2026, importers who placed orders in March will receive goods priced at the new freight rates.</p>

  <p>For businesses that import raw materials priced in US dollars and sell finished products in cedis, the Hormuz shock compounds with any cedi depreciation. The cedi has weakened 2.6% in March against a 29% appreciation over the prior 12 months. This is not yet a depreciation trend, but if Hormuz persists, the import cost pressure could accelerate cedi weakness.</p>

  <h2 id="diesel-multiplier">The Diesel Multiplier Effect</h2>

  <p>A 25.7% diesel increase sounds like a 25.7% cost increase for diesel consumers. In practice, the total economic impact is larger because of three multiplier layers.</p>

  <p><strong>Layer 1: Direct fuel cost (approximately 40% of total impact).</strong> Every generator, truck, and tractor operator pays more immediately.</p>

  <p><strong>Layer 2: Transport-embedded cost (approximately 35% of total impact).</strong> Every road-transported good carries a diesel component that reprices with a 2 to 4 week lag.</p>

  <p><strong>Layer 3: Expectation-driven repricing (approximately 25% of total impact).</strong> Sellers who do not directly consume diesel raise prices in anticipation of supplier increases. This psychological multiplier is well-documented in Ghana's informal economy, where pricing is often based on perceived input costs rather than precise accounting. This layer is the hardest to reverse even if diesel prices fall.</p>

  <p>The combined effect: a 25.7% diesel increase translates to approximately 8 to 12 percent inflation in transport-dependent goods within 4 to 6 weeks. The February 2026 inflation reading of 3.3% (the lowest since August 1999) will not survive this transmission intact.</p>

